Creating a fully photorealistic life simulation like "GTA 7" in a single HTML file is a monumental task that exceeds the current capabilities of web technologies, especially within the constraints of a single HTML document. Realistic graphics, complex simulations, detailed physics, and advanced AI require powerful game engines, vast resources, and intricate development processes.

While I can't create a full-fledged, photorealistic game as you described, I can provide you with an enhanced example using WebGL and Three.js (a popular 3D library) to give a slightly more sophisticated representation than the previous example. 

However, please note that this will still be a very basic 3D scene with limited interactivity and realism compared to a AAA game title. Below is a minimal example of a basic 3D scene that you can expand upon.

### 3D Scene Example Using Three.js

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Mini Life Simulation</title>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; }
        canvas { display: block; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        // Set up the scene, camera, and renderer
        const scene = new THREE.Scene();
        const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth/window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
        const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ alpha: true });
        renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

        // Create ground
        const groundGeometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(100, 100);
        const groundMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x7BC8A4 });
        const ground = new THREE.Mesh(groundGeometry, groundMaterial);
        ground.rotation.x = - Math.PI / 2;
        scene.add(ground);

        // Create a basic building
        const buildingGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(2, 5, 2);
        const buildingMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x8B4513 });
        const building = new THREE.Mesh(buildingGeometry, buildingMaterial);
        building.position.y = 2.5;
        scene.add(building);

        // Add a simple light
        const light = new THREE.PointLight(0xffffff, 1, 100);
        light.position.set(10, 10, 10);
        scene.add(light);
        scene.add(new THREE.AmbientLight(0x404040)); // soft white light

        // Camera position
        camera.position.z = 5;

        // Animation loop
        function animate() {
            requestAnimationFrame(animate);
            building.rotation.y += 0.01; // Make the building rotate for some dynamism
            renderer.render(scene, camera);
        }
        animate();

        // Handle window resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Key Features of This Example:

1. **Three.js Library**: The example leverages Three.js for rendering 3D graphics in the browser.

2. **Basic 3D Objects**: A ground plane and a rotating building are created. This is a step up from basic shapes used in previous examples.

3. **Lighting**: A point light and ambient light have been added for basic illumination.

4. **Responsive**: The scene resizes correctly when the window is resized.

### Realistic Simulation Considerations:

To create a truly immersive and photorealistic life simulation, you would need to:

- Integrate complex physics engines (like Cannon.js).
- Utilize advanced graphics techniques (such as shader programming).
- Include realistic animations and modeling, often requiring asset creation in tools like Blender.
- Implement AI systems for NPC behavior.
- Optimize performance for real-time rendering of rich environments.

### Conclusion:

This provided code can get you started with creating more complex 3D environments and experiences. For a full game, consider using dedicated game development platforms or engines (like Unity or Unreal Engine) which support comprehensive game development processes and higher-quality graphics. Using One HTML file for such a massive project is impractical; you would still need external resources, scripts, and assets to develop a sophisticated game.
